	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Not to mention this would require building a VM into every emulator... seriously restricting how the emulator operates and limiting the kinds of optimizations emu authors can make... on top of slowing down emulation by bringing it a layer of abstraction higher than it needs to be.
<br />
<br />Hardware emulation should definatly be left to the emulator.  And yes... emulating mappers is part of emulating.  "simulating non-CPU hardware", as you put it, is part of emulation (PPU, APU, controllers, mappers, etc -- everything except for software must be done by the emulator).  In fact... "simulating hardware" is pretty much the <em>definition</em> of emulation.

		

